We recommended Management:
To require the Municipal to drop the stale checks from the list of outstanding checks and prepare appropriate Journal Entries;
To instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to monitor the outstanding checks and take appropriate actions on checks not negotiated after six (6) months period.

Instruct the Inventory Committee to fully conduct the physical inventory of all Property, Plant and Equipment owned by the LGU, including its fixed assets; reconcile the RPCPPE to the Accounting records and effect adjustment, if appropriate;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare the RPCPPE on its prescribed format which shall include the actual status of the items of PPE; maintain and renew all Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) with the concerned accountable officer and employees reflected in the RPCPPE; and to prepare an inventory of unserviceable properties for appropriate action; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) of the PPE accounts; and to prepare an adjusting entry to drop from the books properties which could not be located and the unserviceable PPE items.

Exert extra effort to fully implement its priority projects/programs that are envisioned to help in the attainment of social, economic and environmental development; 

Instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to consider the proper timing in the implementation of programs and projects by indicating in the AIP the specific date of implementation for monitoring and control purposes; 

Management to resort to contracting some of its projects to attain economy and efficiency in project implementation; 

Re-create the Project Monitoring Committee/Project Inspection Team that would assist, evaluate and monitor the extent of implementation of programs and projects in order to determine the causes of delay in the implementation.

The end-user offices to meticulously and judiciously prepare the Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) in accordance with Section 7.3.2 of the RIRR of the RA No. 9184 to avoid delay in the implementation of programs and projects;

The BAC Secretariat and the BAC Chairperson to meticulously check the PPMPs prepared by the end-user units before consolidating it to the APP to facilitate the efficient conduct of procurement activities for every procurement project; and

The Municipal Accountant ensure that PPMPs prepared by the end-user units were in accordance to the RIRR of the RA No. 9184 before certifying the correctness of the said Plan.

The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly observe the revised implementing rules and regulations of the Procurement Law;

The BAC Secretariat promptly prepare the minutes of meeting of the Committee in accordance to the RIRR of RA No. 9184; and

The Technical Working Group (TWG) to meticulously verify and validate the eligibility  requirement of the bidder who was declared as the Lowest Calculated Bidder, and to ensure that additional requirements were submitted before declaring the bidder as the Lowest Calculated and Responsive Bidder.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Treasurer to strictly monitor the collections and remittances of the revenue collectors and instruct the revenue collectors to remit their collections daily and intact;
The Revenue Collectors to report and record promptly their collections and remittances on their cashbook

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant fully transfer the remaining unexpended LDRRM fund of CY2015 to the Special Trust Fund Account;
The LDRRMC to prepare the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) for the current year incorporating therewith the utilization of previous years’ unexpended balances of LDRRMF for proper monitoring on the utilization of the LDRRM fund.

We recommended that:
Local Development Council and offices concerned to be specific in the formulation of development projects otherwise, ensure that all implemented projects described in generic terms are duly supported with SB resolution in compliance to Section 22 (c) of the Republic Act No. 7160 and COA Memorandum No. 2010-14;
The Municipal Budget and Municipal Accountant ensure that approved SB Resolutions are submitted before processing disbursement of funds charged against the appropriations of PPAs stated in generic terms.

We recommended that management:
Exert extra effort to fully implement its priority projects/programs that are envisioned to help in the attainment of social, economic and environmental development;
Instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer to consider the proper timing in the implementation of programs and projects by indicating in the AIP the specific date of implementation for monitoring and control purposes;
Management to resort to contracting some of its projects to attain economy and efficiency in project implementation;
Re-create the Project Monitoring Committee/Project Inspection Team that would assist, evaluate and monitor the extent of implementation of programs and projects in order to determine the causes of delay in the implementation.

We recommended that:
The Inspectorate Team meticulously inspect the specifications of the delivered items per delivery receipt and approved purchase order and refrain from accepting items which do not conform with the specifications;
The Management either require the replacement of the product to conform with the specifications and/or rescind the contract and impose liquidated damages against the supplier whichever is appropriate.
